ntuition
A Binary Search Tree (BST) follows a special ordering property:

All nodes in the left subtree have smaller values than the current node.
All nodes in the right subtree have larger values than the current node.

Using this property, we can determine where both target nodes (p and q) lie without exploring the entire tree.

If both p and q have values smaller than the current node, then their Lowest Common Ancestor (LCA) must also lie in the left subtree.
If both have values greater than the current node, then their LCA must lie in the right subtree.
Otherwise, the current node is the point where the paths to p and q diverge (or one of them is the current node itself), making it their Lowest Common Ancestor.

Since we eliminate one entire subtree at every step, we only traverse a single path from the root.

Complexity
Complexity Analysis

Time Complexity: O(h)

We only traverse one path from the root to the answer, where h is the height of the BST.

Balanced BST: O(log n)
Skewed BST: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(h)

The recursion stack can grow up to the height of the tree.

Balanced BST: O(log n)
Skewed BST: O(n)

Code
# Definition for a binary tree node.
# class TreeNode:
#     def __init__(self, x):
#         self.val = x
#         self.left = None
#         self.right = None

class Solution:
    def lowestCommonAncestor(self, root: 'TreeNode', p: 'TreeNode', q: 'TreeNode') -> 'TreeNode':
        def fun(node):
            if node.val > p.val and node.val > q.val: return fun(node.left)
            if node.val < p.val and node.val < q.val: return fun(node.right)
            return node
        return fun(root)
